Overall: the new `src\Extensions\CHAASSupport\EngHubRetrieval.cs` correctly wires CHaaS EngHub retrieval into agent flow by invoking `IEngHubService.SearchAsync(context, ...)`, but it has one clear correctness bug and one high-impact scoping gap.  
Findings (with refs): **Bug (high)** keyword corruption from `s_redundantKeywords` containing `"ICE"` (`EngHubRetrieval.cs:16,23`) because `RemoveRedundantKeywords` does substring replacement (`src\Sdk\ChatRetrieval.cs:331-333`), so queries like “service practices” become “serv practs”; **Gap (high/design+security boundary)** the call `engHubService.SearchAsync(context, keywords, null, cancellationToken)` (`EngHubRetrieval.cs:27-28`) uses the broad overload that always adds unscoped global search (`src\Sdk.Common\EngHub\EngHubService.cs:195-205`, especially `new()` at line 202), so CHaaS grounding IDs are weighted but not enforced, allowing unrelated corpus retrieval; **Test gaps** current tests only verify one happy-path keyword strip and all-redundant fallback, but miss substring-mangling, overload/scoping behavior, null/empty `ClientInfo`, and reference mapping edge cases.  
Worthwhile enhancements: prefer deriving from shared `Sdk.Common` `EngHubRetrieval` base for consistency (`src\Sdk.Common\EngHub\EngHubRetrieval.cs`), add optional strict-mode scoped call for agent contexts (content IDs only, no global fallback unless explicitly enabled), and consider adding an `On(...)` trigger to reduce unnecessary EngHub queries for every team-scope ask.

