Now I have complete context. Here's my review:

---

## CHaaS EngHub Retrieval — Code Review

### 1. SIGNIFICANT: Broader search scope than intended

**File:** `src/Extensions/CHAASSupport/EngHubRetrieval.cs`, line 27

The call `engHubService.SearchAsync(context, keywords, null, cancellationToken)` resolves to the **scope-less overload** (line 195 of `EngHubService.cs`), which internally constructs:

```csharp
scopes = [new(baselineContentIds, ScoreWeight: 1.3f), new()];  // line 202
```

That trailing `new()` is an **empty scope** — it searches the *entire* EngHub corpus at 1.0× weight. So this Team-scoped retrieval returns results from **all EngHub content**, not just the CHaaS content ID `629fb807-...`. This contrasts with every other scoped retrieval (AzureSearch, SEAL, BIC, etc.) which uses the SDK `EngHubRetrieval` base class and calls the **scoped overload** (line 207), restricting results to declared content IDs only.

Because `[When("!state.agent")]` disables the generic EngHub retrieval during agent sessions, this may be intentional to fill the gap. But it means the CHaaS "Team" retrieval is doing General-scope work, and irrelevant global results could crowd out the 3-result limit (`MaximumResults = 3`) before CHaaS-specific content appears.

**Recommendation:** Use the SDK `EngHubRetrieval` base class with hardcoded content IDs, matching all other extensions:

```csharp
[Name("CHAASSupport_EngHub")]
[DisplayName("CHaaS EngHub Docs")]
[When("user.alias = crilopez")]
[RetrievalScope(ChatRetrievalScope.Team)]
public class EngHubRetrieval(IEngHubService service) : Sdk.EngHub.EngHubRetrieval(
    service,
    [new(["629fb807-dcf0-428a-9ea4-206e17255aae"])],
    redundantKeywords: ["CHAAS", "CHaaS", "ICE", "Zoran", "enghub", "eng hub", "docs", "documentation"]
);
```

This is 3 lines of code, eliminates the entire `SearchAsync` override, and guarantees strictly-scoped results.

